00:00:20.570 --> 00:00:22.070
PROFESSOR: So what
we've been trying

00:00:22.070 --> 00:00:26.730
to do is to develop a
description of properties

00:00:26.730 --> 00:00:28.700
of some system,
could be something

00:00:28.700 --> 00:00:34.080
like a gas, that includes
both mechanical as well

00:00:34.080 --> 00:00:36.880
as thermal properties.

00:00:36.880 --> 00:00:39.620
So the first thing
that we decided to do

00:00:39.620 --> 00:00:43.090
was to wait until
this system has

00:00:43.090 --> 00:00:45.940
properties that do not change.

00:00:45.940 --> 00:00:48.340
Further, with the
observation time

00:00:48.340 --> 00:00:51.440
that we are assigning
to this system,

00:00:51.440 --> 00:00:54.160
and then if it is
a gas we can say,

00:00:54.160 --> 00:00:57.000
OK the gas has some
pressure and volume.

00:00:57.000 --> 00:01:01.190
In general, we said that we
can characterize the system

00:01:01.190 --> 00:01:08.810
through a set of displacements
and the conjugate forces which

00:01:08.810 --> 00:01:13.610
are used when we describe
systems that are mechanical.

00:01:13.610 --> 00:01:14.790
Work on them is done.

00:01:14.790 --> 00:01:18.790
We can say that the work
is Jdx, for example.

00:01:18.790 --> 00:01:19.420
OK?

00:01:19.420 --> 00:01:22.310
Then we decided that this
mechanical description

00:01:22.310 --> 00:01:27.210
was not enough because
systems could exchange heat

00:01:27.210 --> 00:01:32.780
and gradually started to build
a more general prescription that

00:01:32.780 --> 00:01:35.540
included the exchange of heat.

00:01:35.540 --> 00:01:38.350
We saw that, for example,
from the zeroth law,

00:01:38.350 --> 00:01:41.310
we could define temperature as
a function of these quantities.

00:01:44.060 --> 00:01:50.920
And that we could also, from
the first law define energy.

00:01:50.920 --> 00:01:56.740
And in particular that
the change in energy,

00:01:56.740 --> 00:02:00.070
which is a function of where
you are in equilibrium.

00:02:00.070 --> 00:02:03.440
So once you say that you
have a system in equilibrium

00:02:03.440 --> 00:02:07.060
you can say what the values
of the x's and J's are.

00:02:07.060 --> 00:02:09.720
You know somehow what
the value of temperature

00:02:09.720 --> 00:02:11.650
is, what the value of energy is.

00:02:11.650 --> 00:02:15.390
And if you were to
make a change in energy

00:02:15.390 --> 00:02:19.350
by some external means
the amount of change

00:02:19.350 --> 00:02:21.470
would either come
from mechanical work

00:02:21.470 --> 00:02:23.657
that you did on the
system, or the heat

00:02:23.657 --> 00:02:24.990
that you supplied to the system.

00:02:28.690 --> 00:02:31.390
Now this expression
is the one that you

00:02:31.390 --> 00:02:37.790
would like to elevate somehow
and be able to compute energy

00:02:37.790 --> 00:02:40.660
as a function of state.

00:02:40.660 --> 00:02:42.760
Kind of keeping in
mind what we would

00:02:42.760 --> 00:02:45.930
do if there was no heat around.

00:02:45.930 --> 00:02:49.640
And we could do things
mechanically, then mechanically

00:02:49.640 --> 00:02:54.570
we could in principle build up
the energy function by changing

00:02:54.570 --> 00:03:00.770
displacements lightly and
calculating the amount of work

00:03:00.770 --> 00:03:04.451
by this formula.

00:03:04.451 --> 00:03:07.770
And basically we
emphasized that you

00:03:07.770 --> 00:03:11.040
would be able to use
a formula such as this

00:03:11.040 --> 00:03:15.800
if you were to make
things sufficiently slowly

00:03:15.800 --> 00:03:17.960
so that at each
stage in the process

00:03:17.960 --> 00:03:20.430
you can calculate
what Ji is, which

00:03:20.430 --> 00:03:22.340
means that at each
stage in the process

00:03:22.340 --> 00:03:25.941
you should be in some kind
of an equilibrium state.

00:03:25.941 --> 00:03:26.440
OK?

00:03:26.440 --> 00:03:30.790
If that was the case, if
you didn't have dQ then

00:03:30.790 --> 00:03:33.840
this would be your
energy function

00:03:33.840 --> 00:03:36.430
and actually once you had the
energy function you could,

00:03:36.430 --> 00:03:40.280
for example, calculate J
as a derivative of energy

00:03:40.280 --> 00:03:42.050
with respect to x.

00:03:42.050 --> 00:03:44.980
So then you also start
thinking about how many

00:03:44.980 --> 00:03:47.750
independent degrees
of freedom do I have.

00:03:47.750 --> 00:03:51.710
Do I really need all of the
set of x's and J's to describe

00:03:51.710 --> 00:03:53.340
my system in equilibrium.

00:03:53.340 --> 00:03:57.740
If additionally once I know the
e, I can derive all of the J's.

00:03:57.740 --> 00:04:00.480
So we have to also
come eventually

00:04:00.480 --> 00:04:04.030
to grips with how many
independent degrees of freedom

00:04:04.030 --> 00:04:06.990
will describe our system.

00:04:06.990 --> 00:04:11.360
Now the first step towards
completing this expression

00:04:11.360 --> 00:04:14.250
was to find what dQ is.

00:04:14.250 --> 00:04:18.329
So we needed another
law of thermodynamics

00:04:18.329 --> 00:04:22.190
beyond zeroth law and first
law that somehow related

00:04:22.190 --> 00:04:24.890
heat and temperature
to each other.

00:04:24.890 --> 00:04:27.780
As we expect that
somehow this expression

00:04:27.780 --> 00:04:30.330
will leave you temperature.

00:04:30.330 --> 00:04:35.930
And what we used was some
version of the second law.

00:04:40.080 --> 00:04:46.260
That was there how heat would
flow from, say, a hot air body

00:04:46.260 --> 00:04:48.160
to a cold air body.

00:04:48.160 --> 00:04:51.970
And Clausius's theorem would say
that you have only heat flowing

00:04:51.970 --> 00:04:54.494
in one particular direction.

00:04:54.494 --> 00:04:57.100
Well, we sort of
introduced the idea

00:04:57.100 --> 00:05:01.490
of engines, which
are machines that

00:05:01.490 --> 00:05:10.690
are used to do work by taking
heat from the heart air body

00:05:10.690 --> 00:05:12.830
to the cold air body.

00:05:12.830 --> 00:05:17.210
And we could define
an efficiency,

00:05:17.210 --> 00:05:22.810
which is work divided by heat
input, which since work is

00:05:22.810 --> 00:05:28.180
the difference between these
two we could write as 1 minus Qc

00:05:28.180 --> 00:05:28.680
over Qh.

00:05:32.700 --> 00:05:35.900
And then we introduced
this special class

00:05:35.900 --> 00:05:39.030
of engines, which were
these Carnot engines.

00:05:43.210 --> 00:05:46.200
And the idea of this class
was that you could run them

00:05:46.200 --> 00:05:47.390
forward and backward.

00:05:47.390 --> 00:05:50.450
They were kind of reversible.

00:05:50.450 --> 00:05:53.830
The were kind of a analogue
of the frictionless type

00:05:53.830 --> 00:05:58.200
of processes that you would use
to construct mechanical energy.

00:05:58.200 --> 00:06:04.650
And we found that these engines
were the most efficient.

00:06:04.650 --> 00:06:07.310
And so the efficiency
of these engines

00:06:07.310 --> 00:06:10.980
was marked only by
the two temperatures.

00:06:10.980 --> 00:06:15.520
So we had the functional form
potentially of efficiency

00:06:15.520 --> 00:06:18.520
as a function of the two
temperatures involved.

00:06:18.520 --> 00:06:22.430
And what we also showed
was that the efficiency

00:06:22.430 --> 00:06:25.330
of any random engine
was going to be

00:06:25.330 --> 00:06:28.670
less than the efficiency
of the Carnot engine

00:06:28.670 --> 00:06:32.360
that is marked by
these two temperatures.

00:06:32.360 --> 00:06:36.290
And by putting some
Carnot engines in series,

00:06:36.290 --> 00:06:39.740
we saw that the good
way to write this

00:06:39.740 --> 00:06:40.930
was something of this form.

00:06:45.330 --> 00:06:48.110
I can in principle
remove the one

