and we wait and go to
some final condition

00:35:32.850 --> 00:35:35.650
of whatever is inside the box.

00:35:35.650 --> 00:35:39.470
I should be able to
calculate entropy

00:35:39.470 --> 00:35:46.160
before and after in order to see
that this change is positive.

00:35:46.160 --> 00:35:46.660
OK?

00:35:46.660 --> 00:35:50.320
But we say entropy is
a function of state.

00:35:50.320 --> 00:35:57.780
And what have I done here
to change this state?

00:35:57.780 --> 00:36:00.810
I cannot calculate entropy
if the system is not

00:36:00.810 --> 00:36:02.520
in equilibrium.

00:36:02.520 --> 00:36:04.890
If the system is in
equilibrium it presumably

00:36:04.890 --> 00:36:07.470
does not change as
a function of time.

00:36:07.470 --> 00:36:10.440
So what is this
expression relevant to?

00:36:10.440 --> 00:36:12.390
The expression is
relevant to when

00:36:12.390 --> 00:36:16.100
you have some kind of a
constraint that you remove.

00:36:16.100 --> 00:36:18.730
So imagine that
let's say there is

00:36:18.730 --> 00:36:23.930
a gas in this room and some
kind of piston that is initially

00:36:23.930 --> 00:36:26.910
clamped to some position.

00:36:26.910 --> 00:36:29.120
Then I can calculate
the entropy of what's

00:36:29.120 --> 00:36:31.450
on the left side, what's
on the right hand side,

00:36:31.450 --> 00:36:33.930
and that would be
my initial entropy.

00:36:33.930 --> 00:36:35.720
I remove the clamp.

00:36:35.720 --> 00:36:39.940
I remove the constraint so
this can slide back and forth.

00:36:39.940 --> 00:36:43.370
And eventually it comes
to another position.

00:36:43.370 --> 00:36:46.510
So then I can again
calculate the final entropy

00:36:46.510 --> 00:36:48.380
from the sum of what's
on the left side

00:36:48.380 --> 00:36:50.100
and what's on the
right hand side.

00:36:50.100 --> 00:36:52.800
And I can see that
entropy is increased.

00:36:52.800 --> 00:36:56.410
So basically this
statement really

00:36:56.410 --> 00:37:01.200
is useful when there is
some internal constraint

00:37:01.200 --> 00:37:03.400
that you can remove.

00:37:03.400 --> 00:37:05.910
And as you remove the
internal constraint,

00:37:05.910 --> 00:37:07.270
the entropy increases.

00:37:07.270 --> 00:37:09.810
So I guess that image
that we all have

00:37:09.810 --> 00:37:13.410
is that if I give you two
pictures of a room, one

00:37:13.410 --> 00:37:17.120
with books nicely arranged
on a shelf and one

00:37:17.120 --> 00:37:19.680
with books randomly
distributed you

00:37:19.680 --> 00:37:22.740
would have no problem
to time order them.

00:37:22.740 --> 00:37:25.210
And actually presumably
there was some constraint

00:37:25.210 --> 00:37:27.730
from the shelf that
was removed and then

00:37:27.730 --> 00:37:29.800
these things fell down.

00:37:29.800 --> 00:37:32.410
So that's the kind
of process for which

00:37:32.410 --> 00:37:36.037
this statement of the
second law is appropriate.

00:37:36.037 --> 00:37:36.620
Any questions?

00:37:40.010 --> 00:37:41.320
OK.

00:37:41.320 --> 00:37:46.350
So that statement is something
about approach to equilibrium.

00:37:49.940 --> 00:37:54.500
But as I said that there was
some initial configuration

00:37:54.500 --> 00:37:59.750
with some constraint and
as a function of removing

00:37:59.750 --> 00:38:01.680
that constraint
the system would go

00:38:01.680 --> 00:38:05.960
from one sort of equilibrium,
constrained equilibrium

00:38:05.960 --> 00:38:11.410
to an unconstrained equilibrium
and this increase of entropy

00:38:11.410 --> 00:38:14.080
tells us in which
direction it would go.

00:38:14.080 --> 00:38:17.470
You can time order
the various processes.

00:38:17.470 --> 00:38:23.050
Now sometimes this adiabatic
way of doing things

00:38:23.050 --> 00:38:25.180
is not the best way.

00:38:25.180 --> 00:38:30.400
And so depending on what it
is that you are looking at,

00:38:30.400 --> 00:38:32.840
rather than looking
at entropy you

00:38:32.840 --> 00:38:36.540
will be looking at
different functions.

00:38:36.540 --> 00:38:39.690
And so the next step is to
construct different types

00:38:39.690 --> 00:38:42.310
of functions that are
useful for telling us

00:38:42.310 --> 00:38:44.820
something about equilibrium.

00:38:44.820 --> 00:38:49.040
Now I'll start doing that by
some function with which you

00:38:49.040 --> 00:38:51.290
are very familiar.

00:38:51.290 --> 00:38:57.170
And has practically
nothing to do

00:38:57.170 --> 00:38:59.300
with entropy and temperature.

00:38:59.300 --> 00:39:01.970
So we are going to look
at mechanical equilibrium.

00:39:07.327 --> 00:39:08.790
OK.

00:39:08.790 --> 00:39:11.720
And so the kind of
prototype of this,

00:39:11.720 --> 00:39:16.980
since we've been thinking in
terms of springs or wires,

00:39:16.980 --> 00:39:20.690
is let's imagine that
I have a wire that

00:39:20.690 --> 00:39:23.490
has some natural lent.

00:39:23.490 --> 00:39:26.970
And it is sitting there
happily in equilibrium.

00:39:26.970 --> 00:39:32.090
And then I attach, let's
say a mast to it and because

00:39:32.090 --> 00:39:36.030
of that I'm pulling
it with a force

00:39:36.030 --> 00:39:37.690
that I will indicate by J.

00:39:37.690 --> 00:39:39.740
So J, if you are
in gravity, would

00:39:39.740 --> 00:39:43.780
be mass of this times J. OK?

00:39:43.780 --> 00:39:47.480
Now if you were doing
things in vacuum,

00:39:47.480 --> 00:39:51.890
what would happen
to your x, which

00:39:51.890 --> 00:39:53.740
is the distortion
that you would have

00:39:53.740 --> 00:39:56.440
from the equilibrium
as a function of time?

00:40:00.590 --> 00:40:03.240
What would happen is
presumably the thing

00:40:03.240 --> 00:40:07.930
would start to oscillate and you
would get something like this.

00:40:07.930 --> 00:40:11.210
But certainly not
equilibrium, but in real world

00:40:11.210 --> 00:40:14.380
there is always friction
that is operating.

00:40:14.380 --> 00:40:16.420
And so if there is
a lot of friction

00:40:16.420 --> 00:40:19.950
what is going to
happen is that your x

00:40:19.950 --> 00:40:24.220
will come to some final value.

00:40:24.220 --> 00:40:29.460
So again, this is a constraint,
which I allowed this to move.

00:40:29.460 --> 00:40:31.700
And because of that
constraint I went

00:40:31.700 --> 00:40:34.530
from the initial equilibrium
that corresponded to x

00:40:34.530 --> 00:40:38.460
equals to 0 to some
final equilibrium.

00:40:38.460 --> 00:40:40.350
And you say, well, if
I want to calculate

00:40:40.350 --> 00:40:42.820
that final equilibrium,
what I need

00:40:42.820 --> 00:40:45.950
to do is to remove all
of the kinetic energy

00:40:45.950 --> 00:40:48.350
so that the thing
does not move anymore,

00:40:48.350 --> 00:40:52.020
which means that I have to
minimize the potential energy.

00:40:52.020 --> 00:40:54.070
I'll give it the
symbol H for reasons

00:40:54.070 --> 00:40:55.790
to become apparent shortly.

00:40:55.790 --> 00:40:58.980
And that is the
sum of the energy

00:40:58.980 --> 00:41:00.990
that I have in the spring.

00:41:00.990 --> 00:41:03.180
Let's imagine that it
is a hook end spring.

00:41:03.180 --> 00:41:06.920
We would have a formula such as
this, plus the potential energy

00:41:06.920 --> 00:41:09.580
that I have in my
mass, which is related

00:41:09.580 --> 00:41:11.780
to how far I go up and down.

00:41:11.780 --> 00:41:18.140
And say an appropriate
description is minus Jx.

00:41:18.140 --> 00:41:18.640
OK?

00:41:18.640 --> 00:41:21.990
So this is the net potential
energy of the spring plus

00:41:21.990 --> 00:41:23.840
whatever is supplying
the mass that

00:41:23.840 --> 00:41:26.290
is applying in the
external force.

00:41:26.290 --> 00:41:31.280
And so in this case, what
you have is that minimizing

00:41:31.280 --> 00:41:36.590
H with respect to
the constraint x

00:41:36.590 --> 00:41:41.600
will give you that the x
equilibrium is J over K. OK?

00:41:41.600 --> 00:41:47.460
So basically it comes
down to J over K.

00:41:47.460 --> 00:41:51.350
And that the value of this
function, potential energy

00:41:51.350 --> 00:41:55.310
function in equilibrium
substituting this over here

00:41:55.310 --> 00:42:01.796
is minus J squared over K. 2K.

00:42:01.796 --> 00:42:02.296
OK?

00:42:06.670 --> 00:42:14.170
So in many processes that
involve thermodynamics

00:42:14.170 --> 00:42:17.490
we are going to do
essentially the same thing.

00:42:17.490 --> 00:42:21.470
And we are going to call this
net potential central energy,

00:42:21.470 --> 00:42:23.954
in fact, an enthalpy.

00:42:23.954 --> 00:42:25.360
OK?

00:42:25.360 --> 00:42:29.090
And the generalized version
of what I wrote down for you

00:42:29.090 --> 00:42:35.880
is the following, in the
process that I described

00:42:35.880 --> 00:42:39.630
which was related to
the increase in entropy

00:42:39.630 --> 00:42:42.085
we were dealing with a
system that was isolated.

00:42:45.090 --> 00:42:49.220
dQ was 0 and there was no work
because the coordinates were

00:42:49.220 --> 00:42:52.040
not changing. dW was 0.

00:42:52.040 --> 00:42:54.890
Whereas here, I am
looking at a process

00:42:54.890 --> 00:42:57.820
where there is a
certain amount of work

00:42:57.820 --> 00:43:04.020
because this external
J that I am putting

00:43:04.020 --> 00:43:06.010
is doing work on the spring.

00:43:06.010 --> 00:43:10.020
It is adding energy
to the spring.

00:43:10.020 --> 00:43:15.080
And the thing is that
because of the friction

00:43:15.080 --> 00:43:17.540
it doesn't continue
to oscillate.

00:43:17.540 --> 00:43:24.410
So some of the energy that I
would have put in the system,

00:43:24.410 --> 00:43:32.670
if I really were using the
formula Jidxi is lost somehow.

00:43:32.670 --> 00:43:37.460
We can see those
oscillations have gone away.

00:43:37.460 --> 00:43:45.310
Now I'm always doing this
process at constant J. Right?

00:43:45.310 --> 00:43:55.134
So if I prescribe for you some
path of x as a function of T,

00:43:55.134 --> 00:44:01.760
Jdx is the same thing as d of
Jx because J does not change.

00:44:01.760 --> 00:44:03.596
x changes.

00:44:03.596 --> 00:44:06.560
OK?

00:44:06.560 --> 00:44:10.830
I'm going to also
imagine processes

00:44:10.830 --> 00:44:20.760
where mechanical equilibrium,
but with no heat so that dQ

00:44:20.760 --> 00:44:21.370
is 0.

00:44:28.220 --> 00:44:31.590
If I were to add
these two together,

00:44:31.590 --> 00:44:34.265
then I will get an
inequality involving

00:44:34.265 --> 00:44:44.110
dE, which is less than or equal
to d of Jixi, which I can write

00:44:44.110 --> 00:44:54.250
as the change in e minus
Jixi has to be negative.

00:44:54.250 --> 00:44:57.330
So appropriate to
processes, which

00:44:57.330 --> 00:45:00.310
are conducted so that
there is mechanical work

00:45:00.310 --> 00:45:04.410
at constant force,
is this function

00:45:04.410 --> 00:45:08.960
that is usually
called H for enthalpy.

00:45:08.960 --> 00:45:14.310
And what we find is that the
dH is going to be negative.

00:45:14.310 --> 00:45:16.140
And again, if you
think about it this

00:45:16.140 --> 00:45:19.410
is precisely this
enthalpy is none other

00:45:19.410 --> 00:45:21.095
than the potential
energy that is

00:45:21.095 --> 00:45:23.270
in the mechanical
degrees of freedom.

00:45:23.270 --> 00:45:27.110
And there's always
loss in the universe.

00:45:27.110 --> 00:45:32.050
And so the direction naturally
is for this potential energy

00:45:32.050 --> 00:45:34.700
to decrease.

00:45:34.700 --> 00:45:42.390
One thing to note
is that dH is dE.

00:45:44.950 --> 00:45:52.860
Thinking of it not now as a
process going on at constant J,

00:45:52.860 --> 00:45:56.620
but as a change in
a function of state

00:45:56.620 --> 00:46:00.320
because we said that
once I prescribe where

00:46:00.320 --> 00:46:04.590
I am in the coordinate
space I know what, say e is.

00:46:04.590 --> 00:46:05.830
I know what J is.

00:46:05.830 --> 00:46:11.130
I can certainly construct a
function, which is e minus Jx.

00:46:11.130 --> 00:46:12.950
It's another function of state.

00:46:12.950 --> 00:46:18.670
And I can ask what happens
if I make a change from one

00:46:18.670 --> 00:46:21.800
point in space to another point.

00:46:21.800 --> 00:46:26.250
Along the path that potentially
allows variations in J dE

00:46:26.250 --> 00:46:27.370
I know, is Jidxi.

00:46:31.980 --> 00:46:34.760
And then, actually I'm
using summation conversion.

00:46:34.760 --> 00:46:39.320
So let's remove that,
plus TdS and here

00:46:39.320 --> 00:46:43.470
it becomes minus
Jidxi minus xidJi.

00:46:47.510 --> 00:46:51.040
Jidxi is cancelled.

00:46:51.040 --> 00:46:59.570
And we that if I construct
the function H as e minus Jx,

00:46:59.570 --> 00:47:04.420
the natural variations
of it are TdS, just

00:47:04.420 --> 00:47:11.215
like dE but rather than
Jdx I have minus xdJ.

00:47:13.965 --> 00:47:16.760
OK?

00:47:16.760 --> 00:47:21.970
So H is naturally expressed as
a function of variables that are

00:47:21.970 --> 00:47:25.720
s and the Ji's.

00:47:25.720 --> 00:47:29.750
And remember that we said we
are doing things at constant J.

00:47:29.750 --> 00:47:32.460
So it's nice that
it happens that way.

00:47:32.460 --> 00:47:36.550
And in particular if I
do partial derivatives

00:47:36.550 --> 00:47:48.610
I find that my xi is minus
dH by dJi at constant s.

00:47:48.610 --> 00:47:50.890
So that in the same
way before I said

00:47:50.890 --> 00:47:55.160
that if you have the energy
function dE by dx will give J,

00:47:55.160 --> 00:48:00.212
if you have the H functions,
dH by dJ would give you x.

00:48:00.212 --> 00:48:00.920
Let's check.

00:48:00.920 --> 00:48:04.310
Here we had an H function.

00:48:04.310 --> 00:48:11.020
If I do a dH by dJ with a
minus sign, what do I get?

00:48:11.020 --> 00:48:14.810
I will get J over K. What
was my equilibrium x?

00:48:14.810 --> 00:48:18.415
It was J over K. OK?

00:48:32.860 --> 00:48:37.030
Now both of these functions
that we have encountered so far

00:48:37.030 --> 00:48:41.670
were expressing
the system energy

00:48:41.670 --> 00:48:47.535
or enthalpy have as
their argument entropy.

00:48:47.535 --> 00:48:52.190
Now if I give you a box you will
have a hard time potentially

00:48:52.190 --> 00:48:57.110
figuring out what entropy
is, but varying temperature

00:48:57.110 --> 00:48:59.580
is something that
we do all the time.

00:48:59.580 --> 00:49:02.930
So it would be great if we
could start expressing things

00:49:02.930 --> 00:49:05.930
not in terms of entropy,
in terms of anything else.

00:49:05.930 --> 00:49:09.020
Well, what's the natural
thing if not entropy?

00:49:09.020 --> 00:49:11.840
Here we went from x to
the conjugate variable

00:49:11.840 --> 00:49:17.670
J. I can make a transformation
that goes from s

00:49:17.670 --> 00:49:22.780
to the conjugate variable,
which is temperature.

00:49:22.780 --> 00:49:25.760
And that would be
relevant, therefore,

00:49:25.760 --> 00:49:30.000
when I'm thinking about
isothermal processes.

00:49:30.000 --> 00:49:34.720
And so what I'm going to do is
to reverse the role of the two

00:49:34.720 --> 00:49:41.420
elements of energy
that I had previously

00:49:41.420 --> 00:49:43.340
for mechanical processes.

00:49:43.340 --> 00:49:48.710
So what we had there
was that dQ was 0,

00:49:48.710 --> 00:49:50.480
but I want dQ to be non-0.

00:49:53.170 --> 00:49:56.720
What we had there was
that dW was non-0.

00:49:56.720 --> 00:50:00.880
So let's figure out
processes where dW is 0,

00:50:00.880 --> 00:50:05.230
but dQ, the same way that
previously we were doing dW

00:50:05.230 --> 00:50:13.780
at constant J, let's do dQ
not equals to 0 at constant T.

00:50:13.780 --> 00:50:18.570
And constant T is where the
isothermal expression comes

00:50:18.570 --> 00:50:19.900
into play.

00:50:19.900 --> 00:50:21.920
OK?

00:50:21.920 --> 00:50:32.760
So if dW is 0, I have a natural
inequality that involves dQ.

00:50:32.760 --> 00:50:35.680
I just erased it, I think.

00:50:35.680 --> 00:50:36.180
Yeah.

00:50:36.180 --> 00:50:37.190
It's not here.

00:50:37.190 --> 00:50:40.226
dQ is less than or equal to TdS.

00:50:43.410 --> 00:50:46.800
And if T is a constant
throughout the process,

00:50:46.800 --> 00:50:50.356
I can write this as d of TS.

00:50:50.356 --> 00:50:55.890
Add these two together
to get that dE less than

00:50:55.890 --> 00:51:03.820
or equal to d of TS, or
taking it to the other side,

00:51:03.820 --> 00:51:06.895
I can define a function which
is the Helmholtz free energy.

00:51:13.200 --> 00:51:18.070
F, which is E minus TS.

00:51:18.070 --> 00:51:21.270
And what we have is that
the natural direction

00:51:21.270 --> 00:51:24.590
of flow for free
energy when we remove

00:51:24.590 --> 00:51:27.810
some kind of a constraint
at constant temperature

00:51:27.810 --> 00:51:33.540
is that we will tend to
minimize the free energy.

00:51:33.540 --> 00:51:38.860
And then again doing
the manipulation of dF

00:51:38.860 --> 00:51:47.760
is dE minus d of TS in general
will have minus TdS minus SdT.

00:51:47.760 --> 00:51:51.720
The TdS part of the E will
vanish and what I will have

00:51:51.720 --> 00:51:59.410
is Jidxi minus SdT.

00:51:59.410 --> 00:52:02.560
So now we can see that
finally for the free energy,

00:52:02.560 --> 00:52:06.490
the Helmholtz free energy,
and natural variable

00:52:06.490 --> 00:52:12.540
rather than being entropy
is the temperature and all

00:52:12.540 --> 00:52:14.857
set of displacements.

00:52:14.857 --> 00:52:17.190
And then if you ask, well,
what happened to the entropy?

00:52:17.190 --> 00:52:21.560
You say, well, I can get
the entropy as minus dF

00:52:21.560 --> 00:52:23.805
by dT at constant x.

00:52:51.030 --> 00:52:52.740
If I take this
picture of the gas

00:52:52.740 --> 00:52:57.740
that I had put at the beginning,
which was just erased,

00:52:57.740 --> 00:53:00.980
picture of a piston
that can slide.

00:53:00.980 --> 00:53:02.770
And I think of that
as a box that I

00:53:02.770 --> 00:53:06.070
bring into this room, well,
then if you'll quickly

00:53:06.070 --> 00:53:09.560
adjust to the
temperature of the room,

00:53:09.560 --> 00:53:12.220
as well as the
pressure of the room.

00:53:12.220 --> 00:53:16.120
So this is going to be a
general transformation in which

00:53:16.120 --> 00:53:20.500
both heat and the
work are exchanged.

00:53:20.500 --> 00:53:25.410
If is at external temperature
and pressure that is fixed.

00:53:25.410 --> 00:53:33.801
So it's a transformation that
is isothermal and constant J.

00:53:33.801 --> 00:53:35.550
In pressure you would
call it [INAUDIBLE].

00:53:39.230 --> 00:53:40.610
OK?

00:53:40.610 --> 00:53:42.300
And then quite
generally you would

00:53:42.300 --> 00:53:45.940
say extending what
we had before,

00:53:45.940 --> 00:53:53.660
in this case dQ is, again, less
than TdS because of Clausius.

00:53:53.660 --> 00:54:00.490
dW is less than Jdx
because you always

00:54:00.490 --> 00:54:07.300
lose something to friction.

00:54:07.300 --> 00:54:09.670
You always lose
something to friction.

00:54:09.670 --> 00:54:12.100
You add the two things
together, and you

00:54:12.100 --> 00:54:18.630
get that dE is less than or
equal to TdS, plus Jidxi.

00:54:21.360 --> 00:54:23.940
For the transformations
that we are considering

00:54:23.940 --> 00:54:29.100
that are at constant
t and J I can

00:54:29.100 --> 00:54:33.860
take these expressions to
mean the same thing as d

00:54:33.860 --> 00:54:43.450
of ts plus Jixi, which
means that more generally,

00:54:43.450 --> 00:54:53.060
