This is a statement
about most things

01:12:00.900 --> 01:12:05.550
that we encounter around
us, but once you go,

01:12:05.550 --> 01:12:08.890
let's say, to the cosmos,
and you have a star,

01:12:08.890 --> 01:12:12.050
the gravitational
energy of the star

01:12:12.050 --> 01:12:14.280
is not proportional
to its volume.

01:12:14.280 --> 01:12:18.260
It goes the size to
some fractional power.

01:12:18.260 --> 01:12:22.910
So that is an example of a
system because of the way

01:12:22.910 --> 01:12:25.620
gravity works as a
long range force, that

01:12:25.620 --> 01:12:28.300
is not extensive system.

01:12:28.300 --> 01:12:31.510
Typically this
would work as long

01:12:31.510 --> 01:12:34.110
as you have interactions
among your elements

01:12:34.110 --> 01:12:36.200
that are sufficiently
short-ranged

01:12:36.200 --> 01:12:40.720
so that you don't
get non-extensivity.

01:12:40.720 --> 01:12:44.130
If that's the case then
I can take a derivative

01:12:44.130 --> 01:12:48.860
of this expression with respect
to lambda, evaluated at lambda

01:12:48.860 --> 01:12:51.900
equals 2, 1.

01:12:51.900 --> 01:12:54.440
If I take a derivative
with respect to lambda

01:12:54.440 --> 01:13:02.960
here I will have dE by
dS, times S. I mean,

01:13:02.960 --> 01:13:04.800
the argument here
is lambda S. I am

01:13:04.800 --> 01:13:08.090
taking a derivative with
respect to the first argument.

01:13:08.090 --> 01:13:12.810
So I bring out a factor of
S. dE by dS at constant x

01:13:12.810 --> 01:13:18.885
and N. And then the next
term is xi dE with respect

01:13:18.885 --> 01:13:23.000
to all the different
xi's at constant S and N.

01:13:23.000 --> 01:13:30.380
Next one is going to be
N alpha, dE by dN alpha

01:13:30.380 --> 01:13:36.480
at constant x and S. And
there's only one lambda

01:13:36.480 --> 01:13:40.350
on this side, which is
going to give me E of Sx.

01:13:43.154 --> 01:13:43.654
OK?

01:13:46.530 --> 01:13:52.110
Now if I look at my
initial expression

01:13:52.110 --> 01:13:56.000
I can immediately see that
dE by dS at constant x

01:13:56.000 --> 01:13:59.830
and N is none other
than T. So this

01:13:59.830 --> 01:14:05.010
is the same thing as T.
dE by dxi at constant s

01:14:05.010 --> 01:14:07.970
and n is none other than Ji.

01:14:07.970 --> 01:14:15.120
dE by dN alpha at constant x and
Js is none other than mu alpha.

01:14:15.120 --> 01:14:20.130
So once I set the argument to be
1, so that all of these things

01:14:20.130 --> 01:14:22.850
are evaluated at
lambda equals to 1,

01:14:22.850 --> 01:14:30.450
I have the result that e is
equal to TS plus Jixi, plus mu

01:14:30.450 --> 01:14:33.010
alpha N alpha.

01:14:33.010 --> 01:14:41.430
So in some sense all I did was
I took the more fundamental

01:14:41.430 --> 01:14:45.070
expression and removed
all of the d's.

01:14:45.070 --> 01:14:48.440
So some places, this is called
the fundamental relation,

01:14:48.440 --> 01:14:54.455
but I don't like that because it
is only valued for systems that

01:14:54.455 --> 01:14:57.020
are extensive, whereas
the initial formula

01:14:57.020 --> 01:15:00.300
is valued irrespective of that.

01:15:00.300 --> 01:15:01.800
OK?

01:15:01.800 --> 01:15:05.610
Now once I have
this what I can do

01:15:05.610 --> 01:15:09.230
is I can think of
this as a relationship

01:15:09.230 --> 01:15:12.550
among different
functions of state.

01:15:12.550 --> 01:15:18.540
Take a derivative and
write it as dE is d of TS.

01:15:18.540 --> 01:15:26.530
D of TS is TdS plus SdT, plus
d of Jixi, which gives me

01:15:26.530 --> 01:15:34.340
Jidxi plus xidJi,
plus d of mu alpha.

01:15:34.340 --> 01:15:37.340
And alpha will give
me mu alpha dn alpha,

01:15:37.340 --> 01:15:40.895
plus N alpha d mu alpha.

01:15:40.895 --> 01:15:41.870
OK?

01:15:41.870 --> 01:15:45.140
This is just a rewriting
of this expression

01:15:45.140 --> 01:15:47.290
in differential form.

01:15:47.290 --> 01:15:54.430
But I know that dE is the
same thing as TdS plus Jdx

01:15:54.430 --> 01:15:55.590
plus mu n alpha.

01:15:59.610 --> 01:16:05.820
So immediately what it tells me
is that the intensive variables

01:16:05.820 --> 01:16:23.580
T, J, and mu our constrained
to satisfy this relation, which

01:16:23.580 --> 01:16:33.261
is called a
Gibbs-Duhem relation.

01:16:33.261 --> 01:16:33.760
OK?

01:16:36.510 --> 01:16:43.530
So this is, if you like,
the mathematical reason

01:16:43.530 --> 01:16:46.700
for my answer before.

01:16:46.700 --> 01:16:56.040
That I cannot choose this set of
variables to describe my system

01:16:56.040 --> 01:17:00.040
because this set of variables
are not independent.

01:17:00.040 --> 01:17:03.790
If I vary two of them the
variation of the other one

01:17:03.790 --> 01:17:05.090
is fixed.

01:17:05.090 --> 01:17:09.880
And I said I need N plus 1
independent degrees of freedom.

01:17:09.880 --> 01:17:14.070
If I choose all of
the intensive ones

01:17:14.070 --> 01:17:20.110
I'm really using one additional
relationship that relates them,

01:17:20.110 --> 01:17:21.660
makes them dependent.

01:17:21.660 --> 01:17:23.580
And of course this
also goes to the fact

01:17:23.580 --> 01:17:27.640
that I won't know what the size
of the system is, both of them

01:17:27.640 --> 01:17:28.900
reflections of extensivity.

01:17:31.500 --> 01:17:37.620
Just as an example, let's see.

01:17:37.620 --> 01:17:43.840
Chemical potential
along isotherm.

01:17:51.920 --> 01:17:57.610
So for a gas, what would I have?

01:17:57.610 --> 01:18:05.310
I would write SdT minus Vdp.

01:18:05.310 --> 01:18:10.310
That is my contribution from
the work here remembering

01:18:10.310 --> 01:18:14.150
