01:18:14.150 --> 01:18:20.670
And then I have N
d mu equals to 0.

01:18:20.670 --> 01:18:26.170
I said how do these
vary along an isotherm?

01:18:26.170 --> 01:18:30.700
Isotherm means that I have
to set dT equals to 0.

01:18:30.700 --> 01:18:35.040
If I'm along an isotherm
then I have that d mu

01:18:35.040 --> 01:18:38.070
is rearranging
things a little bit.

01:18:38.070 --> 01:18:40.530
Mu over NdP.

01:18:40.530 --> 01:18:45.010
So this is the formula
that I will have to use.

01:18:45.010 --> 01:18:48.660
Now let's specialize to
the case of an ideal gas.

01:18:48.660 --> 01:18:52.870
So I'm going to use
here an ideal gas.

01:18:52.870 --> 01:18:56.640
For the case of the ideal
gas we had the relationship

01:18:56.640 --> 01:18:59.700
that PV was NKT.

01:18:59.700 --> 01:19:03.580
So v over n is the same
