01:20:07.210 --> 01:20:11.520
Very briefly to be
expanded upon next lecture,

01:20:11.520 --> 01:20:15.420
the other set of
mathematical relations

01:20:15.420 --> 01:20:18.150
go under the name of
Maxwell relations.

01:20:26.430 --> 01:20:29.123
And they follow from the
following observation.

01:20:33.960 --> 01:20:37.450
If I have a function of
more than one variable,

01:20:37.450 --> 01:20:44.840
let's say, f of x and y, two
variables, then the natural way

01:20:44.840 --> 01:20:47.240
to write this
consistent with what

01:20:47.240 --> 01:20:54.860
we had before is that df is df
by dx partial at constant ydx,

01:20:54.860 --> 01:20:58.900
plus dfy, the y
at constant x dy.

01:21:01.820 --> 01:21:05.190
But one thing that
we know from calculus

01:21:05.190 --> 01:21:08.920
is that these are
first derivatives,

01:21:08.920 --> 01:21:12.430
and there are a bunch
of second derivatives.

01:21:12.430 --> 01:21:18.100
In particular, the second
derivative d2 f, dx, dy

01:21:18.100 --> 01:21:24.660
is independent of the order
of taking the derivatives.

01:21:24.660 --> 01:21:27.630
Which means that if I take
a derivative of this object

01:21:27.630 --> 01:21:30.200
with respect to y, I
will get the same thing

01:21:30.200 --> 01:21:33.570
if I were to take a derivative
of the second object

01:21:33.570 --> 01:21:36.310
with respect to x.

01:21:36.310 --> 01:21:42.200
So in particular if I go back
to my fundamental equation,

01:21:42.200 --> 01:21:45.290
dE, let's forget about
the chemical potential

01:21:45.290 --> 01:21:52.630
because time is running
short, Jidxi plus TdS.

01:21:52.630 --> 01:21:57.810
I identify T and Ji as
the first derivatives.

01:21:57.810 --> 01:22:02.070
That is, Ji is the
first derivative of e

01:22:02.070 --> 01:22:05.895
with respect to xi
at constant S. T

01:22:05.895 --> 01:22:08.560
is the first derivative
of E, with respect

01:22:08.560 --> 01:22:11.420
to S at constant x.

01:22:11.420 --> 01:22:16.760
Then if I were to take a second
derivative to construct d2E

01:22:16.760 --> 01:22:26.270
with respect to x and T, and
S, I could do it two ways.

01:22:26.270 --> 01:22:31.060
I already have a derivative with
respect to x that gave me Ji,

01:22:31.060 --> 01:22:33.590
so I take another
derivative of J

01:22:33.590 --> 01:22:38.020
with respect to S,
now at constant x.

01:22:38.020 --> 01:22:40.820
Or I can take a
derivative here, which

01:22:40.820 --> 01:22:52.240
is dT by dxi at constant
S. And depending

01:22:52.240 --> 01:22:58.990
on which one of the many
functions of state that we

01:22:58.990 --> 01:23:04.250
introduced, E, F, G,
H, you can certainly

01:23:04.250 --> 01:23:08.500
make corresponding second
derivative inequalities.

01:23:08.500 --> 01:23:13.040
And the key to sort of
understanding all of them

01:23:13.040 --> 01:23:16.020
is this equality of
second derivatives.

01:23:16.020 --> 01:23:18.850
So what I will start
next time around

01:23:18.850 --> 01:23:23.270
is to just give you a set
of things on the left hand

01:23:23.270 --> 01:23:24.680
side, the analog of this.

01:23:24.680 --> 01:23:29.860
So for example, I could
